# Testing Standards

## General Principles

- Every test follows Arrange-Act-Assert structure
- Test behavior, not implementation details
- One logical assertion per test (multiple related asserts are fine)
- Test names describe the scenario and expected outcome

## Frontend Testing (Jest + React Testing Library)

### File Placement

- Test files live next to the component: `ExpenseCard.test.jsx` beside `ExpenseCard.jsx`
- Test utilities and mocks in `src/__tests__/helpers/`

### Naming

- Describe blocks mirror component name: `describe('ExpenseCard', ...)`
- Test names use "should" pattern: `it('should display expense amount', ...)`

### Patterns

```jsx
// Query by role/text, never by test-id unless no semantic alternative
screen.getByRole('button', { name: /submit/i })
screen.getByText(/total expenses/i)

// User interactions via userEvent, not fireEvent
await userEvent.click(submitButton)
await userEvent.type(input, 'Coffee')

// Async assertions with findBy
expect(await screen.findByText(/saved/i)).toBeInTheDocument()
```

### Mocking

- Mock API calls with `jest.mock()` on the service module
- Mock Redux store with a test utility that wraps components in `<Provider>`
- Mock `react-router-dom` navigation with `MemoryRouter`
- Reset mocks in `beforeEach` to prevent test pollution

## Backend Testing (JUnit 5 + Spring Boot Test)

### File Placement

- Tests mirror source structure: `src/test/java/com/expense/service/ExpenseServiceTest.java`
- Integration tests use `@SpringBootTest`; unit tests use plain JUnit + Mockito

### Naming

- Test classes: `{ClassName}Test.java` for unit, `{ClassName}IntegrationTest.java` for integration
- Test methods: `shouldReturnExpenseWhenIdExists()`

### Patterns

```java
// Unit test with Mockito
@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)
class ExpenseServiceTest {
    @Mock ExpenseRepository repository;
    @InjectMocks ExpenseServiceImpl service;

    @Test
    void shouldReturnExpenseWhenIdExists() {
        when(repository.findById(1L)).thenReturn(Optional.of(expense));
        ExpenseResponse result = service.findById(1L);
        assertThat(result.getAmount()).isEqualTo(expected);
    }
}

// Integration test
@SpringBootTest
@AutoConfigureMockMvc
class ExpenseControllerIntegrationTest {
    @Autowired MockMvc mockMvc;

    @Test
    void shouldCreateExpense() throws Exception {
        mockMvc.perform(post("/api/expenses")
            .contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)
            .content(json))
            .andExpect(status().isCreated());
    }
}
```

### Mocking

- Use `@MockBean` to replace Spring beans in integration tests
- Use `@Mock` + `@InjectMocks` for pure unit tests
- Use `@DataJpaTest` for repository layer tests with H2
- Never mock the class under test
